  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".[106]",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[106] See also the elaborate dissertation on the apost. benedictory greeting by Otto in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jahrb. für D. Theol.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 1867, p. 678 ff. The origin of that greeting, however, is hardly to be traced back, as the author holds, to the Aaronic blessing, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 6:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f. Otherwise it would always be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "tripartite",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and, in particular, would not omit the characteristic ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔλεος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Now, the only Epistles in which it certainly occurs as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "tripartite",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔλεος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", are the (post-Pauline) ones, 1 and 2 Tim. and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 John 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (but with a peculiar variation). It was only at a later date that the Aaronic blessing passed over into Christian liturgic use (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Constitt. ap.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ii. 57. 13); but a free reminiscence of that blessing may already be contained in the greetings of those late Epistles.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
